{{en-verb|past2=het|past2_qual=dialectal}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause an increase in temperature of (an object or space); to cause to become [[hot]] {{qualifier|often with "up"}}.
#: ''I'll '''heat''' up the water.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become hotter.
#: ''There's a pot of soup '''heating''' on the stove.''
# {{lb|en|transitive|figurative}} To excite or make hot by action or emotion; to make feverish.
#* William Shakespeare
#*: Pray, walk softly; do not '''heat''' your blood.
# {{lb|en|transitive|figurative}} To excite ardour in; to rouse to action; to excite to excess; to inflame, as the passions.
#* John Dryden
#*: A noble emulation '''heats''' your breast.
# {{lb|en|transitive|slang}} To [[arouse]], to [[excite]] (sexually).
#: ''The massage '''heated''' her up.''

